(68, 1, '2013-02-15 00:07:37', '2013-02-14 18:07:37', 'At a low level, there is no such thing as a multi-dimensional array. There is just a flat block of memory, large enough to hold a given number of elements. In C, a multi-dimensional array is conceptually an array whose elements are also arrays. So if you do:\r\n\r\n[cpp]\r\nint array[2][3];\r\n[/cpp]\r\n\r\nConceptually you end up with:\r\n\r\n[cpp]\r\narray[0] =&gt; [0, 1, 2]\r\narray[1] =&gt; [0, 1, 2]\r\n[/cpp]\r\n\r\nThis results in the elements being arranged contiguously in memory, because array[0] and array[1] are not actually holding any data, they are just references to the two inner arrays. Note that this means that only the [0, 1, 2] entries actually occupy space in memory. If you extend this pattern out to the next dimension, you can see that:\r\n\r\n[cpp]\r\nint array[2][3][2];\r\n[/cpp]\r\n\r\n...will give you a structure like:\r\n\r\n[cpp]\r\narray[0] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1]\r\n            [1] =&gt; [0, 1]\r\n            [2] =&gt; [0, 1]\r\narray[1] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1]\r\n            [1] =&gt; [0, 1]\r\n            [2] =&gt; [0, 1]\r\n[/cpp]\r\n\r\nWhich continues arranging the elements consecutively in memory (as above, only the [0, 1] entries actually occupy space in memory, everything else is just part of a reference to one of these entries). As you can see, this pattern will continue no matter how many dimensions you have.\r\nAnd just for fun:\r\n\r\n[cpp]\r\nint array[2][3][2][5];\r\n[/cpp]\r\n\r\nGives you:\r\n\r\n[cpp]\r\narray[0] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n                   [1] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n            [1] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n                   [1] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n            [2] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n                   [1] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\narray[1] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n                   [1] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n            [1] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n                   [1] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n            [2] =&gt; [0] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n                   [1] =&gt; [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]\r\n[/cpp]\r\n\r\n<strong>What is the meaning of int (*p)[5], char *x[3][4], int *(*a[10])() and int (*t[])() ?</strong>\r\n<strong>Ans :</strong>\r\n<strong>int (*p)[5] :</strong> A pointer to an array of 5 integers.\r\n<strong>char *x[3][4] :</strong> x is an composed of "3 arrays of 4 pointers to character".\r\n<strong>int *(*a[10])() :</strong> An array of 10 pointers to functions returning an integer pointer.\r\n<strong>int (*t[])() :</strong> An array of pointers to function returning an integer pointer.', 'Multi-dimensional array in C/C++', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'multi-dimensional-array-in-cc', '', '', '2014-07-20 00:42:18', '2014-07-19 18:42:18', '', 0, 'http://localhost:90/mdarif/?p=68', 0, 'post', '', 0),
