(114, 1, '2014-08-10 17:53:06', '2014-08-10 11:53:06', '<h1 style="font-size: 1.2em; text-align: center;">Difference between JavaScript, Jquery and Ajax</h1>\n        <div class="para">\n                <b style="color: #ff6600;">JavaScript : </b>Javascript is a client side scripting language provided by the browser so that we can do a level of programming on client side. client side scripting means that the browser will execute the script into.\n        </div>\n        <div class="para">\n                <b style="color: #ff6600;">jQuery : </b>jQuery is the most popular javascript framework. Why use it? Different browser has different idea about how javascript is implemented. jQuery takes a care of this difference and provided us with a unified and very easy way to do coding in javascript.\n        </div>\n        <div class="para">\n                <b style="color: #ff6600;">AJAX(Asynchronous Javascript and XML) : </b>AJAX is a mechanism to fetch data from server without doing a full page load. We need to use javascript to make a ajax call, and we need it again when data is returned from server. AJAX is a mechanism, not a language javascript or framework like jQuery.\n        </div>\n        <h1 style="font-size: 1.2em; text-align: center;">What is DOM ?</h1>\n        <div class="para">\n            <b style="color: #ff6600;">DOM(Document Object Model) : </b>When a webpage is parsed by the browser, it creates an in-memory representation of the page. It is a tree structure, which contains all elements on the page. So there is a root element, which contains the head and the body elements, which contain other elements. So it looks like a tree basically. Now with javascript we can manipulate elements in the page using this tree. We can pick elements by their id (getElementsById), or their tag name (getElementsByTagName), or by simply going through the tree (parentNode, firstChild, lastChild, nextSibling, previousSibling, etc.). Once we have element(s) to work with we 